🛑 Stop vilifying carbs, even if you’re on a weight loss diet. 🥯 

It is common belief that cutting carbs offers some metabolic advantage in weight loss. Yes, given the thermic effect of different foods, carbs result in less TEE compared to fat or protein, but data shows that there is no substantial difference. Carbs are the body’s main energy source and can help optimise physical and mental performance.

Adherence to a diet causes sustained weightless, and no special diet has yet shown a clinically meaningful superiority. It all boils down to what works for you so that you can stay on that diet longer.

Once more, louder, for those in the back: 
You do not need to be super thin to be healthy. 

Studies found that lowest mortality rate is found in women with around 35% body fat or lower and in men with 22% body fat or lower. 

So yes, low body fat % is great for health. But you can be healthy at 35% body fat also. 

If you’re looking at being healthy, take realistic and sustainable steps and have realistic goals. 

@powerlifterdietitian has an excellent post on this study. Go read it.

No, we don’t have the same 24hrs. Let me explain. 

🔶Careers: Depending upon the job, sometimes it is not possible to then travel to a gym and try to get a workout in, or even to go running at odd hours when it may not be safe. I know people who go to work at 7am and get back home at 9pm and then have to sort out their meals, plus make time for chores. 

🔶Finances: Some people have to choose other things (like food, shelter) over gym memberships. Yes, they can go running. But then again, there’s work and household chores. Consider that finances come in play even with regard to nutrition, sometimes. 

🔶Kids: People with kids just do not have as many hours as we do. 

🔶Priority: Work, time with family, rest, household chores, and so many more things can take up priority in a person’s life. 

Yes, people should make time for movement and try to eat as well as they can. In India we are lucky to have veggies super cheap compared to highly processed foods. Getting even a few hours of exercise and eating as well as you can will greatly improve your quality of life and overall health and energy. 

But let us not kid ourself by claiming that a fitness influencer with no kids, whose job is to exercise, has the same 24hrs that a person with kids, a regular job, and a whole lot of responsibilities does.

Hard truth: little girls as young as 5 start worrying about dieting.
Not because they were born hating their bodies—
But because they watched the women around them do it.

Mothers skipping meals.
Aunties talking about “cheat days.”
Compliments only when you lose weight.

✨ They’re listening. They’re watching. ✨
We owe them a better story.
We deserve a better story.
Life should be more than shrinking ourselves to fit a dress size.

Let’s break the cycle.
Let them grow up knowing their worth has nothing to do with their weight. 💔➡️❤️

.
.
.
.
.

#BreakTheCycle #BodyImageHealing #GenerationalHealing #GirlsDeserveBetter #StopDietCulture #NormalizeNormalBodies #BodyAcceptance #AntiDietCulture #SelfWorthNotSize #WomenSupportingWomen

It’s time to STOP FEARING MUSCLES! 💪 The idea that strength training makes women “bulky” is simply a myth. Beyond aesthetics, building and maintaining muscle is absolutely vital for your long-term health, especially as we age.

Here’s why every woman needs to embrace strength training:

🌟 Combats Sarcopenia: Directly fights age-related muscle loss, preserving your strength, mobility, and metabolism.

🌟 Fights Osteoporosis: Weight-bearing exercises are crucial for increasing bone density, strengthening your skeleton against fractures.

🌟 Boosts Metabolic Health: More muscle means better insulin sensitivity and blood sugar control, reducing Type 2 Diabetes risk and aiding healthy weight management.

🌟 Enhances Balance & Prevents Falls: Stronger muscles improve coordination, significantly lowering fall risk as you age.

🌟 Supports Joint Health: Building strength around joints stabilizes them, reducing pain and improving function.

Swipe through my feed, and you’ll see a lot of smiles, strong workouts, and happy moments. And you know what? That’s by design. Because social media is a highlight reel. It’s a carefully curated space, a collection of the moments I choose to share.

Why would I post crying content? Why would I share the exhaustion after a tough session, the moments of self-doubt, or the quiet struggles we all face? Because this platform, for me, is about inspiring, motivating, and sharing the energy that keeps me going. It’s about putting out positivity, not necessarily broadcasting every raw, unedited second of real life.

And that’s okay. Because real life is not social media. My life isn’t always sunshine and PRs. Just like yours, it has its challenges, its quiet moments, its frustrations, and days where simply showing up is the biggest win. We’re all just figuring it out, one day at a time, often without a filter or the perfect angle.

So, when you scroll, remember: everyone’s feed is their chosen narrative. Let it inspire you, connect you, but never make you feel less than. Your real, messy, beautiful life, off-screen, is where the true magic happens. ❤️

.
.
.
.
.

Can we stop expecting all “fit” people to look like bodybuilders? 😅

Fitness is not one-size-fits-all — and definitely not one-body-type-fits-all.

A runner’s body? Built for endurance, not bulk.
A triathlete? Needs efficiency, stamina, and strength across three disciplines — not 6-pack abs.
A swimmer? Prioritizes shoulder mobility and lung capacity over shredded aesthetics.
Even elite athletes in these sports often don’t have visible abs or ultra-low body fat. And guess what? They’re still incredibly fit. 💪

Being fit isn’t about how you look, it’s about what your body can do.
Endurance, speed, mobility, strength, power, recovery, adaptability — that’s fitness.

Let’s stop measuring fitness with just a mirror. 🧠
Let’s stop thinking abs = health. ❤️
Let’s start celebrating different bodies for their unique strengths and capabilities. 🚴‍♀️🏃‍♀️🏊‍♀️

.
.
.
.
.

✨ Not all progress is visible. ✨

You might not see dramatic before-after photos, but you’re feeling it:
💪 You’re stronger.
💖 You’re lighter in spirit.
🧠 You’re mentally clearer.
👖 Your clothes fit differently because your body is rebuilding itself—stronger, healthier, better.

Sometimes, it’s not about the mirror.
It’s about carrying your groceries without help.
It’s about walking up stairs without gasping.
It’s about playing longer with your kids.
It’s about joy in motion.

Keep going. The work you’re putting in? It’s changing you in the best ways—even if you can’t always see it. 🌱
